07035nam a22013455i 9780691184494DE-B159720210927121507.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210927t20182019nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911844947 a10.1515/97806911844942doi  a(DE-B1597)501683  a(OCoLC)1059351063  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aBX1490 7aREL0150002bisacsh04a282/.42231 aVélez, Karin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Miraculous Flying House of Loreto :bSpreading Catholicism in the Early Modern World /cKarin Vélez. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (312 p.) :b7 b/w illus., 1 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tPart I. First Landings -- tCHAPTER 1. Introduction -- tCHAPTER 2. Deconstructing a Miracle -- tPart II. Approaching Loreto -- tCHAPTER 3. First Authors -- tCHAPTER 4. Accidental Pilgrims -- tPart III. Leaving Loreto -- tCHAPTER 5. Holy House Builders -- tCHAPTER 6. Anonymous Renovators of Icons -- tCHAPTER 7. Counters, Namers, and Processers -- tPart IV.New Departures -- tCHAPTER 8. Reconstructing Catholic Expansion -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1295, a house fell from the evening sky onto an Italian coastal road by the Adriatic Sea. Inside, awestruck locals encountered the Virgin Mary, who explained that this humble mud-brick structure was her original residence newly arrived from Nazareth. To keep it from the hands of Muslim invaders, angels had flown it to Loreto, stopping three times along the way. This story of the house of Loreto has been read as an allegory of how Catholicism spread peacefully around the world by dropping miraculously from the heavens.In this book, Karin Vélez calls that interpretation into question by examining historical accounts of the movement of the Holy House across the Mediterranean in the thirteenth century and the Atlantic in the seventeenth century. These records indicate vast and voluntary involvement in the project of formulating a branch of Catholic devotion. Vélez surveys the efforts of European Jesuits, Slavic migrants, and indigenous peoples in Baja California, Canada, and Peru. These individuals contributed to the expansion of Catholicism by acting as unofficial authors, inadvertent pilgrims, unlicensed architects, unacknowledged artists, and unsolicited cataloguers of Loreto. Their participation in portaging Mary's house challenges traditional views of Christianity as a prepackaged European export, and instead suggests that Christianity is the cumulative product of thousands of self-appointed editors. Vélez also demonstrates how miracle narratives can be treated seriously as historical sources that preserve traces of real events.Drawing on rich archival materials, The Miraculous Flying House of Loreto illustrates how global Catholicism proliferated through independent initiatives of untrained laymen.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Sep 2021) 7aRELIGION / Christianity / History.2bisacsh  aAgostinho de Santa Maria.  aAntónio Cordeiro.  aBishop Casal.  aCaravaggio.  aCardinal Antonio Maria Gallo.  aCardinal Rutilio Benzoni.  aCatholic devotion.  aCatholic pilgrims.  aCatholicism.  aChristianity.  aEuropean Jesuits.  aFrancisco de Florencia.  aGirolamo Angelitta.  aHoly House of Loreto.  aHoly House.  aItaly.  aJesuits.  aJuan Maria Salvatierra.  aLaureta.  aLoreto.  aMadonna of Loreto.  aMarian art.  aMarian sanctuaries.  aMary's house.  aMary.  aMoxos missions.  aNicolà Albani.  aPierre Chaumonot.  aPietro di Giorgio Tolomei.  aRoman paintin